", "newString": "## ✔️ Circuit Breaker

You can opt in to a per-origin circuit breaker to stop hammering an unhealthy origin. It is disabled by default and only applies when you pass the `circuitBreaker` option.

After `threshold` consecutive failures for an origin, the circuit **opens** and further requests fail fast with a `Circuit breaker is open` error (without calling `fetch`). After `cooldown` milliseconds it moves to **half-open** and allows up to `halfOpenMaxRequests` probe requests: a successful probe closes the circuit, a failed probe re-opens it and restarts the cooldown.

```ts
await ofetch("http://unstable.example/api", {
  circuitBreaker: true, // use defaults
});

await ofetch("http://unstable.example/api", {
  circuitBreaker: {
    threshold: 5, // consecutive failures before opening (default: 5)
    cooldown: 30000, // ms to wait before a half-open probe (default: 30000)
    halfOpenMaxRequests: 1, // concurrent probes allowed while half-open (default: 1)
    // response statuses counted as failures
    // (default: [408, 409, 425, 429, 500, 502, 503, 504])
    failureStatusCodes: [500, 502, 503, 504],
  },
});
```

Circuit state is keyed by the request **origin** (not path) and is shared between clients created via `.create()`. A logical request counts as a single failure even when internal retries occur. Network errors, body/parse errors, and interceptor exceptions all count as failures, while responses with non-listed status codes do not affect the circuit.

